wenty-first century, combining legal analysis with a focus on institutional relations, particularly the interactions between federal judges and administrators. Melnick argues that years of ambiguous, inconsistent, and meandering Court decisions left lower court judges adrift, forced to apply contradictory Supreme Court precedents in a wide variety of highly charged political and educational contexts. As a result, desegregation policy has been a patchwork, with lower court judges playing a crucial role and with little opportunity to analyze what worked and what didn’t. The Crucible of Desegregation reveals persistent patterns and disagreements that continue to roil education policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEducation and statezUnited States. 0aEducation and state-United States. 0aSchool integrationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aSchool integrationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSchool integration-Law and legislation-United States. 0aSegregation in educationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aSegregation in education-Law and legislation-United States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBrown v. Board of Education, Supreme Court, desegregation, color-blindness, racial isolation, resegregation, civil rights state, equal educational opportunity, Office for Civil Rights, termination cases.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete e